==English==

===Etymology===
{{der|en|la|-}} {{compound|la|floccus|t1=a wisp|naucum|t2=a trifle|nihilum|t3=nothing|pilus|t4=a hair|nocat=1}} + {{m|en|-fication}}

A jocular coinage, apparently by pupils at {{w|Eton College}}, combining a number of roughly synonymous Latin stems. The word was inspired by a line in the ''Eton Latin Grammar'' that gave a rule for certain verbs that take some words irregularly in the genitive case: “{{m|la|flocci|Flocci}}, {{m|la|nauci}}, {{m|la|nihili}}, {{m|la|pili}}, {{m|la|assis}}, {{m|la|huius}}, {{m|la|teruncii}}, {{m|la|[[his]] [[verbis]]}}, {{m|la|aestimo}}, {{m|la|pendo}}, {{m|la|facio}}, {{m|la|[[peculiariter]] [[adduntur]]}}”.<ref>{{cite-web |title=''Floccinaucinihilipilification'' |publisher=''The Spectator'' |work=Mind your language |author=Dot Wordsworth |url=https://www.spectator.co.uk/2011/06/mind-your-language-39/ |date=11 June 2011}}.</ref> This translates loosely to: “The words {{m|la|floccus}}, {{m|la|naucus}}, {{m|la|nihilum}}, {{m|la|pilus}}, {{m|la|assis||penny}}, {{m|la|hic||this}} and {{m|la|teruncius||farthing}} are irregularly used with the genitive case with these verbs: {{m|la|aestimo||to appraise value}}, {{m|la|pendo||to weigh, to pay}}, {{m|la|facio||to make}}”.

